<section class="intro-section mb-12">
  <h3 id="mission">Mission</h3>
  <p>
    <strong>Web Intl</strong> standardizes <strong>localization</strong> — turning a single
    UI into many locales. The web platform already ships the hard parts of <em>formatting individual
    values</em> through <a href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/Intl"><code>Intl</code></a>
    (numbers, dates, plurals, lists, segmentation, display names) and <em>direction</em> through
    <code>dir</code>, <code>:dir()</code>, and CSS logical properties. What it does not ship is
    <em>composing messages</em>, <em>managing translation catalogs</em>, and <em>switching locale
    reactively</em> — the work every framework re-solves with its own i18n library. This project owns
    that gap. It defines the contract (via the <a href="/intents/locale/">Locale Intent</a>), a shared
    <a href="/plugs/customtranslationproviderregistry/">translation provider registry</a> that any
    consumer delegates to, and the <a href="#protocol-localization">Localization Protocol</a> that
    conformant implementations satisfy.
  </p>
  <p>
    Translation providers are <strong>pluggable and ordered</strong>: the first registered provider that
    resolves a message key for the active locale owns the message. Native <code>Intl</code> message
    formatting (Unicode MessageFormat 2.0), bundled catalogs, lazy-loaded namespaces, and library
    adapters (FormatJS, i18next, Lingui, Paraglide) are all equal participants — registered by the
    application, not hardwired into the standard.
  </p>

  <div class="comparison-block" style="background: rgba(99, 102, 241, 0.08); padding: 1.25rem; border-radius: 8px; border-left: 4px solid #4f46e5; margin: 1.5rem 0;">
    <h4 style="margin-top: 0; color: #4338ca; font-size: 1rem;">Localization vs. native <code>Intl</code></h4>
    <p style="margin-bottom: 0; font-size: 0.95rem;">
      Native <strong><code>Intl</code></strong> formats <em>one value</em> for a locale — a price, a
      date, a plural category. <strong>Localization</strong> is everything around that: composing a
      message from static text plus formatted values, resolving a key against a catalog, walking a
      <strong>fallback chain</strong> when a locale lacks a translation, loading catalogs lazily, and
      re-rendering when the locale changes. The protocol leans on native <code>Intl</code> as its
      default formatter and adds only the composition and catalog layer the platform is missing.
    </p>
  </div>
</section>

<section id="features" class="section-card">
  <h3 id="feature-surface">Feature Surface</h3>
  <p>
    What a localization standard covers, and how each capability is fulfilled.
    <strong>Built-in</strong> = provided by native <code>Intl</code> or a conformant provider;
    <strong>Adapter</strong> = delegated to a third-party library behind the registry;
    <strong>Compose</strong> = deferred to an existing Web Everything standard.
  </p>
  <div style="overflow-x: auto; max-width: 100%;">
    <table style="min-width: 680px;">
      <thead>
        <tr><th>Feature</th><th>Applies To</th><th>What it does</th><th>Built-in</th><th>Adapter / Compose</th></tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
