<section id="how" class="section-card">
  <h3 id="how-it-works">How It Works</h3>
  <p>
    A consumer never bundles a translation table. It reads messages through the reactive <code>@t</code>
    context, which resolves the active locale's provider through the injector chain and formats the
    message with native <code>Intl</code>:
  </p>
  {% highlight "html" %}
<!-- The @t context resolves a key for the active locale and formats it. -->
<span>@t.greeting</span>
<span>@t.itemCount({ count: $store.items.length })</span>
  {% endhighlight %}
  {% highlight "typescript" %}
// 1. Register providers at application bootstrap (priority order).
import { Mf2Provider } from '@web-intl/messageformat';
import { I18nextProvider } from '@web-intl/i18next';

customTranslations.define('app', new Mf2Provider({ load: (l) => import(`./locales/${l}.json`) }));
customTranslations.define('vendor', new I18nextProvider(i18nextInstance)); // adapter, equal participant

// 2. Any consumer resolves a key — it never knows which provider answered.
function t(key: string, params?: Record<string, unknown>): string {
  for (const provider of customTranslations.values()) {
    const message = provider.resolve(key, locale.value); // MessageFn | null
    if (message) return message(params);                 // first that resolves wins
  }
  return key; // missing-key fallback
}
  {% endhighlight %}
  <ul style="font-size: 0.9rem; color: var(--color-text-muted); margin-top: 1rem;">
    <li><strong>One contract:</strong> the <a href="/plugs/customtranslationprovider/"><code>CustomTranslationProvider</code></a> interface — <code>resolve(key, locale): MessageFn | null</code> — satisfied by every provider alike.</li>
    <li><strong>One registry:</strong> <a href="/plugs/customtranslationproviderregistry/"><code>CustomTranslationProviderRegistry</code></a> (<code>window.customTranslations</code>) holds providers in priority order.</li>
    <li><strong>One message shape:</strong> <code>type MessageFn = (params?: Record&lt;string, unknown&gt;) =&gt; string</code> — the common interface for runtime (MF2) and compile-time (Paraglide-style) messages alike.</li>
  </ul>
</section>

<section id="protocol-localization" class="section-card">
  <h3 id="localization-protocol">Localization Protocol</h3>
  <p>
    Conformance reference for localization interop. Defines the
    <a href="/plugs/customtranslationprovider/"><code>CustomTranslationProvider</code></a> contract, the
    <a href="/plugs/customtranslationproviderregistry/"><code>CustomTranslationProviderRegistry</code></a>
    resolution pattern, the MF2 message-function shape, and the observable states any conformant
    consumer must satisfy. The protocol never prescribes a message library or catalog format; native
    <code>Intl</code> is the default formatter and every other engine plugs in behind the registry.
  </p>

  <h4 id="scope-localization">Scope: Message Composition &amp; Locale Negotiation</h4>
  <p>
    The Localization Protocol owns <strong>resolving a key to a formatted message for the active
    locale</strong> — catalog lookup, fallback-chain walking, MF2 formatting, and the observable load
    states around lazy catalogs. It does <strong>not</strong> own writing direction or format
    preferences (the <a href="/intents/locale/">Locale Intent</a> declares those) nor the reactive
    locale value itself (a <a href="/projects/webstates/"><code>CustomStore</code></a>).
  </p>

  <h4 id="consumer-pattern">How Consumers Use the Registry</h4>
  <p>
    A conformant consumer must <strong>never embed a translation table</strong>. It resolves
    <code>CustomTranslationProviderRegistry</code> through the injector chain and delegates, walking the
    locale fallback chain until a provider resolves the key:
  </p>
  {% highlight "typescript" %}
// Conformant resolution pattern.
function resolveMessage(
    key: string,
    locale: string,
    params?: Record<string, unknown>,
): string {
    const registry = /* resolve customTranslations from injector chain */;
    const chain = negotiate(locale);          // e.g. ['fr-CA', 'fr', 'en']

    for (const tag of chain) {
        for (const provider of registry.values()) {
            const message = provider.resolve(key, tag);  // MessageFn | null
            if (message === null) continue;              // Provider declined — try next.
            return message(params);                      // First that resolves owns the message.
        }
    }
    return key;   // No provider resolved — surface the key (missing-key strategy).
}
  {% endhighlight %}

  <h4 id="observable-states">Observable States</h4>
  <p>A conformant consumer reflects these states while a catalog loads or a key is missing:</p>
  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr><th>State</th><th>Condition</th><th>Maps To</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr>
        <td><code>loading</code></td>
        <td>The active locale's catalog is being fetched lazily (the <a href="/intents/translation/">Translation Intent</a> <code>async</code> strategy)</td>
        <td><a href="/intents/loader/">Loader Intent</a> (skeleton / soft block)</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><code>ready</code></td>
        <td>A provider resolved the key; the formatted message is rendered</td>
        <td>—</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><code>missing-key</code></td>
        <td>No provider resolved the key across the whole fallback chain</td>
        <td>Missing-key strategy (render key, or dev-time warning)</td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <h4 id="web-standards-alignment">Web Standards Alignment</h4>
  <table>
    <tr><th>Standard</th><th>Status</th><th>How We Adopt It</th></tr>
    <tr>
      <td><a href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/Intl"><code>Intl.*</code></a></td>
      <td>Baseline</td>
      <td>The default formatter for numbers, dates, plurals, lists, and display names embedded in messages. Providers format values with native <code>Intl</code> rather than re-implementing CLDR.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><a href="https://unicode.org/reports/tr35/tr35-messageFormat.html">Unicode MessageFormat 2.0</a></td>
      <td>Unicode standard (2024)</td>
      <td>The default message syntax — variable interpolation, plural/gender <code>.match</code>, extensible function registry. Polyfilled until <code>Intl.MessageFormat</code> ships.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><a href="https://github.com/tc39/proposal-intl-messageformat"><code>Intl.MessageFormat</code></a></td>
      <td>TC39 Stage 1</td>
      <td>The forward-compatible target. The MF2 provider is the polyfill the native API will eventually replace, with no change to the <code>MessageFn</code> shape.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><a href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTML/Global_attributes/dir"><code>dir</code> / <code>:dir()</code></a></td>
      <td>Baseline</td>
      <td>Writing direction is driven by the <a href="/intents/locale/">Locale Intent</a> <code>direction</code> dimension; components adapt via CSS logical properties and <code>:dir()</code>.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><a href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/Navigator/languages"><code>navigator.languages</code></a></td>
      <td>Baseline</td>
      <td>The default signal for locale detection and negotiation when no explicit URL/cookie preference exists.</td>
    </tr>
  </table>

  <h4 id="interface">Interface</h4>
  {% highlight "typescript" %}
/** The common message shape — runtime (MF2) and compile-time messages alike. */
type MessageFn = (params?: Record<string, unknown>) => string;

/** Contract every translation provider implements.
 *  Return a MessageFn to own the key for that locale; return null to decline. */
abstract class CustomTranslationProvider {
    abstract resolve(key: string, locale: string): MessageFn | null;
}

/** Locale negotiation: expand a requested locale into an ordered fallback chain. */
interface LocaleNegotiation {
    negotiate(requested: string, available: string[]): string[]; // ['fr-CA','fr','en']
}

/** Formats an MF2 message source against the active locale, leaning on Intl.* . */
interface MessageFormatter {
    compile(source: string, locale: string): MessageFn;
}
  {% endhighlight %}

  <h4 id="design-decisions">Design Decisions</h4>
  <ul style="font-size: 0.9rem;">
    <li><strong>Native-first formatter:</strong> messages compose native <code>Intl</code> output. The protocol adds the composition and catalog layer the platform lacks — it never re-implements number/date/plural formatting.</li>
    <li><strong>MF2 over ICU 1.0:</strong> the default message syntax is Unicode MessageFormat 2.0 — a published Unicode standard and the syntax <code>Intl.MessageFormat</code> will expose — so today's polyfill becomes tomorrow's native call with no source change. ICU 1.0 / Fluent remain available as adapters.</li>
    <li><strong>First-that-resolves:</strong> providers are tried in registration order; the first whose <code>resolve()</code> returns a non-null <code>MessageFn</code> owns the message. Mirrors <code>CustomRecoveryHandler</code> (<code>tryRecover</code>) and route matching (<code>matchRoute</code>).</li>
    <li><strong>Null means decline:</strong> a provider returning <code>null</code> declines a key without side effects; resolution continues down the fallback chain. No separate <code>has()</code> predicate is needed.</li>
    <li><strong>No built-in catalog:</strong> the protocol ships no messages. Applications register the providers (bundled MF2, lazy namespaces, library adapters) they actually need.</li>
  </ul>

  <h4 id="exports">Exports</h4>
  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr><th>Export</th><th>Kind</th><th>Description</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td><code>CustomTranslationProvider</code></td><td>Abstract Class</td><td>Base contract all providers extend</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>MessageFn</code></td><td>Type</td><td><code>(params?) =&gt; string</code> — the resolved, formattable message</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>LocaleNegotiation</code></td><td>Interface</td><td>Expands a requested locale into an ordered fallback chain</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>MessageFormatter</code></td><td>Interface</td><td>Compiles an MF2 source into a <code>MessageFn</code></td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>
</section>

<section id="composition" class="section-card">
  <h3 id="composition">Composition With Other Standards</h3>
  <p>
    Web Intl owns <em>message composition and locale negotiation</em>, not <em>how the
    locale is stored</em>, <em>how load states are shown</em>, or <em>which way the layout flows</em> —
    those compose with neighbouring standards:
  </p>
  <ul style="font-size: 0.9rem;">
    <li><strong><a href="/intents/locale/">Locale Intent</a></strong> — the declarative preference axis; active <code>locale</code>, writing <code>direction</code> (LTR/RTL/auto), and optional numbering/calendar. The protocol's <code>realizesIntent</code> target.</li>
    <li><strong><a href="/intents/translation/">Translation Intent</a></strong> — the UX delivery axis; whether switching locale is <code>instant</code> (preloaded), <code>async</code> (lazy-loaded behind a loading state), or <code>reload</code> (per-locale document load). Orthogonal to <em>which</em> locale is active.</li>
    <li><strong><a href="/projects/webstates/">Web States</a> (<code>CustomStore</code>)</strong> — holds the reactive locale value; a change re-renders every <code>@t</code> binding like any other observable state.</li>
    <li><strong><a href="/intents/loader/">Loader Intent</a></strong> — loading-state UX (skeleton, soft block) shown while a lazy catalog is fetched.</li>
    <li><strong>Router</strong> — URL-based locale routing (<code>/fr/…</code> → locale store) via a <code>&lt;route-view&gt;</code> locale parameter.</li>
    <li><strong><a href="/projects/webadapters/">Web Adapters</a></strong> — FormatJS, i18next, Lingui, and Paraglide bridges register as providers behind the same contract.</li>
  </ul>
</section>

<section id="status" class="section-card">
  <h3 id="status">Status</h3>
  <p>
    Web Intl is in <strong>concept</strong> phase. The contract and provider registry are
    specified via the <a href="#protocol-localization">Localization Protocol</a>; an MF2 message-format
    provider, a lazy-namespace provider, and library adapters (FormatJS / i18next / Lingui / Paraglide)
    are the first planned implementations. Grounded in the
    <a href="/research/internationalization/">Internationalization &amp; Translation</a> research.
  </p>
  <h4 style="margin-top: 1rem;">Open Questions</h4>
  <ul style="font-size: 0.9rem; color: var(--color-text-muted);">
    <li>Ship an MF2 polyfill now, or wait for <code>Intl.MessageFormat</code> (Stage 1, potentially years out)?</li>
    <li>Offer both runtime (plugged) and compile-time (unplugged, Paraglide-style tree-shaken functions) modes, or pick one default?</li>
    <li>Normalize translation file formats (JSON / PO / XLIFF / ARB / Fluent) at build time, or constrain to one canonical format?</li>
    <li>Should the missing-key strategy (render key vs. throw vs. dev-warn) be a Locale Intent dimension or a registry option?</li>
  </ul>
</section>
